His definition of liberty, influenced by Joseph Priestley and Josiah Warren, was that the individual ought to be free to do as he wishes unless he harms others.[132] However, although Mill's initial economic philosophy supported free markets and argued that progressive taxation penalised those who worked harder,[133] he later altered his views toward a more socialist bent, adding chapters to his Principles of Political Economy in defence of a socialist outlook and defending some socialist causes,[134] including the radical proposal that the whole wage system be abolished in favour of a co-operative wage system.
